---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';

const WORKSHOP_TITLE = 'Practical Generative AI Workshops for Teams | Auston Horras';
const WORKSHOP_DESCRIPTION =
	'Practical generative AI workshops for teams and leaders. Learn how to work with AI effectively using clear workflows, constraints, and real-world examples.';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={WORKSHOP_TITLE} description={WORKSHOP_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<div class="page-shell">
			<header class="main-nav">
				<nav class="container nav-inner" aria-label="Primary">
					<a href="/" class="brand">austontatious.dev</a>
					<div class="nav-links">
						<a href="/#hero">Portfolio</a>
						<a href="/#projects">Projects</a>
						<a href="/workshops/" aria-current="page">Workshops</a>
					</div>
					<div class="nav-actions">
						<a href="mailto:auston.horras@gmail.com">Email</a>
						<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/auston-horras-17022614/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
							LinkedIn
						</a>
					</div>
				</nav>
			</header>

			<main class="workshop-main">
				<section class="section workshop-hero">
					<div class="container section-inner">
						<p class="eyebrow">Executive Workshop Offering</p>
						<h1>Your Team Has AI. Why Aren’t You Seeing the Productivity Gains?</h1>
						<p class="lead workshop-lead">
							You already invested in AI tools. This workshop helps your teams use them in ways that produce
							clear, consistent operational value.
						</p>
						<p class="workshop-intro">
							Many organizations have already rolled out AI, allocated budget, and raised expectations around
							productivity. The return is often inconsistent because teams are still using modern AI systems
							with outdated mental models and trial-and-error workflows.
						</p>
						<div class="workshop-hero-actions">
							<a class="button button-primary" href="mailto:auston.horras@gmail.com?subject=AI%20Workshop%20Inquiry">
								Inquire About a Workshop
							</a>
							<a class="button button-secondary" href="#format">See Workshop Format</a>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="container section-inner workshop-content">
						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>The AI Productivity Gap</h2>
							<p>
								Leaders are being asked where the AI return is. Teams have access to capable tools, but
								usage patterns are uneven and outcomes vary widely across roles.
							</p>
							<ul>
								<li>Some employees produce strong results while others get little value</li>
								<li>Leadership sees rising AI spend but inconsistent performance gains</li>
								<li>Teams are experimenting, but there is no shared operating model</li>
								<li>Output quality, speed, and confidence vary person to person</li>
							</ul>
						</article>

						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>The Problem Isn’t Another Platform</h2>
							<p>
								This is not a software pitch. It is not platform reselling. Most organizations already have
								access to powerful AI systems.
							</p>
							<p>
								The missing piece is a practical framework teams can use to apply those tools effectively and
								consistently in real work.
							</p>
						</article>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="container section-inner workshop-content">
						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>Most AI Training Hasn’t Kept Up</h2>
							<p>
								The field has moved quickly, and much of the training available to teams has not kept pace
								with how modern models actually behave.
							</p>
							<p>
								Many programs still overemphasize isolated prompt tricks or role-play style prompting as the
								main lever. Teams need workflow-level methods that produce repeatable results.
							</p>
						</article>

						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>The Gap Between AI Capability and Team Adoption</h2>
							<p>
								Engineers building modern AI systems understand these tools differently than day-to-day
								knowledge workers expected to use them.
							</p>
							<p>
								Internal technical leads often understand integration, but organizations still need a
								translation layer that turns model behavior into practical team habits. This workshop is that
								translation layer.
							</p>
						</article>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="container section-inner workshop-content">
						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>What Your Team Walks Away With</h2>
							<ul>
								<li>A shared framework for using AI effectively across roles</li>
								<li>More consistent quality and speed in AI-assisted output</li>
								<li>Better judgment about where AI is useful versus risky</li>
								<li>Practical methods for scope, context, and constraint-driven prompting</li>
								<li>Workflows teams can apply immediately in writing, analysis, planning, and operations</li>
							</ul>
						</article>

						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>Why This Perspective Is Different</h2>
							<p>
								Many workshops are delivered from outside implementation reality. This workshop is taught
								from the perspective of someone who actually builds AI systems and intelligent-agent
								workflows.
							</p>
							<p>
								The focus is translating how modern AI behaves into practical business usage, not trend
								commentary. RN experience is also relevant for teams operating in regulated or
								high-accountability environments.
							</p>
						</article>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="container section-inner workshop-content">
						<article class="workshop-panel" id="format">
							<h2>Workshop Format</h2>
							<ul>
								<li>60-minute executive briefings</li>
								<li>2–4 hour team workshops</li>
								<li>Customized sessions for technical, operational, or cross-functional teams</li>
								<li>Available remotely or on-site</li>
							</ul>
						</article>

						<article class="workshop-panel">
							<h2>Example Live Demos</h2>
							<ul>
								<li>Turning inconsistent AI usage into a repeatable workflow</li>
								<li>Converting rough ideas into structured plans or technical specifications</li>
								<li>Comparing weak prompting habits with modern constraint-driven workflows</li>
								<li>Using AI to critique and strengthen business documents</li>
							</ul>
						</article>
					</div>
				</section>

				<section class="section">
					<div class="container section-inner">
						<div class="workshop-cta">
							<h2>Bring Real AI Productivity Into Daily Team Work</h2>
							<p>
								If your organization has already invested in AI tools but is not yet seeing the productivity
								gains it expected, I can help your teams use these systems effectively in real workflows.
							</p>
							<div class="cta-actions">
								<a class="button button-primary" href="mailto:auston.horras@gmail.com?subject=AI%20Workshop%20Inquiry">
									Contact by Email
								</a>
								<a
									class="button button-secondary"
									href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/auston-horras-17022614/"
									target="_blank"
									rel="noreferrer"
								>
									LinkedIn
								</a>
							</div>
							<a class="back-link workshop-back-link" href="/#hero">Back to portfolio</a>
						</div>
					</div>
				</section>
			</main>

			<footer class="site-footer">
				<div class="container footer-inner">
					<p>Calm systems for clear outcomes.</p>
					<div class="footer-links">
						<a href="mailto:auston.horras@gmail.com">Contact</a>
						<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/auston-horras-17022614/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
							LinkedIn
						</a>
						<a href="https://github.com/austontatious" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">GitHub</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</footer>
		</div>
	</body>
</html>
